# Day 56 – Task I-2: Updating the SSP to Reflect As-Implemented Reality | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Closing the Gap Between Documentation and Reality

Days 54 and 55 completed the Task I-1 implementation verification — working through every technical and administrative control, confirming configurations match SSP documentation, correcting discrepancies, and documenting gaps in the POA&M. Task I-2 takes the output of that verification work and closes the loop: updating the SSP to reflect the as-implemented state of the system.

The distinction between the SSP as written during the Select step and the SSP as updated during Task I-2 is the distinction between planned implementation and verified implementation. The Select-step SSP documented what controls would be implemented and how. The Task I-2 SSP documents what controls have been implemented, with specific evidence references, implementation dates, verification dates, and any adjustments made during implementation that differ from the original plan.

This matters for the assessment team in a very practical way. An assessor reviewing an SSP that says "MFA is enforced for all users" and an SSP that says "MFA is enforced for all users via TOTP authenticator app; enforcement verified [date]; all [N] active accounts confirmed enrolled as of [date]; verification evidence in assessment package Section 4.2" have fundamentally different starting points for their work. The first SSP tells the assessor what to look for. The second SSP tells the assessor what to look for and where the evidence is. That difference affects the efficiency and outcome of the entire assessment.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Task I-2 requires that the SSP be updated to reflect the results of control implementation — specifically that implementation descriptions be updated to reflect actual implementation details, that evidence references be added, and that any deviations from the planned implementation be documented with their rationale.

I also worked on two structural elements that make the SSP maintainable over time: a version control approach and a discrepancy log that captures what changed between the Select-step SSP and the as-implemented SSP.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified Task I-2 is that SSP updating is not just adding dates to existing entries — it is a substantive quality improvement to the documentation.

During the Select step, implementation descriptions were written prospectively — describing what would be implemented. Some of those descriptions were necessarily general because the specific configuration details were not yet finalized. During Task I-2, those general descriptions are replaced with specific, verifiable statements that include the exact configuration, the verification date, the evidence reference, and the responsible party who verified it.

The difference between "RDS encryption is enabled using AWS KMS" (prospective) and "RDS instance [openmrs-prod-db] encryption is enabled using customer-managed KMS key arn:aws:kms:[region]:[account-id]:key/[key-id] (alias: openmrs-rds-encryption); annual rotation enabled; verified [date] by IT Administrator; evidence: RDS console screenshot in assessment package Section 5.1" (as-implemented) is the difference between a description that enables the assessor to know what to verify and one that enables them to go directly to the evidence.

Writing at that level of specificity also disciplines the documenter — it forces confrontation with the actual implementation state rather than relying on the assumption that what was planned is what was deployed.

