## SSP Version Control Approach

Before working through the as-implemented updates, I established a version control structure for the SSP. Without version control, the SSP becomes a document where the current state cannot be distinguished from prior states — and where changes cannot be traced to the decisions and events that caused them.

**SSP versioning convention:**

Major version (v1.0, v2.0): Changes to scope, categorization, or major control decisions — events that require AO review and re-approval of the affected sections.

Minor version (v1.1, v1.2): Implementation updates, evidence additions, and POA&M status changes that do not alter the security posture commitments — these are reviewed by the ISSO and noted in the revision log, but do not require a full AO re-review.

Patch version (v1.1.1): Typographical corrections, formatting changes, evidence reference updates — no substantive content changes.

**SSP Revision Log format:**

| Version | Date | Author | Change Summary | AO Review Required |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| v1.0 | [date] | ISSO | Initial SSP — Select step documentation | Yes — completed [date] |
| v1.1 | [date] | ISSO | Task I-1/I-2 as-implemented updates; 4 discrepancy corrections; POA&M additions | No — implementation updates only |
| v1.1.1 | [date] | ISSO | CloudTrail evidence reference added; AT-2 gap documented | No |

The revision log is maintained as the first section of the SSP, so any reader can immediately identify the current version and understand what has changed.

