## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While working through the version control structure for the SSP today, I came across the circumstances of the **2020 Blackbaud breach** — which I covered on Day 34 from the vendor governance perspective — but want to revisit specifically through the documentation currency lens.

Blackbaud is a cloud software provider that serves many nonprofits and healthcare organizations. The 2020 ransomware attack that compromised Blackbaud's systems affected hundreds of their customers, many of whom were covered entities or business associates under HIPAA. Post-incident analysis revealed that many of the affected organizations had documentation of their data sharing arrangements with Blackbaud — BAAs, ISAs — but those documents had not been reviewed or updated to reflect the actual data being shared. Organizations had grown their use of Blackbaud services over time, and the ePHI scope in the current arrangement was broader than what the original documentation recorded.

The gap between documentation and reality — the same gap that Task I-2 closes for the SSP — meant that when the breach occurred, affected organizations did not have an accurate picture of what data was at risk. Breach notification scope assessments were complicated by the fact that current data inventories did not match the original documentation.

SSP documentation currency is the same discipline applied to the security control picture. If the SSP documents 35-day backup retention when 90-day was specified, and an incident occurs requiring recovery of data from 45 days ago — the SSP suggests a recovery capability that does not exist. If the SSP documents SSH restricted to named administrators when the actual configuration permits unrestricted SSH, an assessor reviewing only the SSP would not know to test the SSH configuration.

Documentation currency is not bureaucratic overhead. It is the difference between an accurate security picture and a false one. Task I-2 is the discipline of ensuring the SSP reflects the system that actually exists.

