## What I Am Still Thinking About

One open question from today's documentation work: how frequently should the SSP be reviewed for currency between formal Task I-2 exercises?

The RMF process envisions a formal SSP update at implementation (Task I-2) and continuous monitoring that feeds POA&M updates on an ongoing basis. But configuration changes happen continuously — every change management record potentially represents a change to the implemented state of a control. If the SSP is only formally updated at Task I-2 during initial implementation, it may drift significantly from the actual configuration over the life of the authorization.

The continuous monitoring strategy from Day 52 requires monthly change log review. I want to add a monthly SSP currency check to that review — the ISSO reviews the past month's change log and identifies any changes that require SSP updates. Minor version updates to the SSP happen monthly rather than only at formal re-authorization events. This keeps the SSP accurate without requiring a full re-documentation exercise at each annual assessment.

This monthly currency check connects the change management process (CM-3) directly to the SSP maintenance process — every change that affects a control implementation description triggers a corresponding SSP update. The connection between those two processes is what prevents the documentation-reality gap from accumulating between assessments.

